revision.text:
'''Asiya''' ({{lang-ar|آسيا}}), alternatively '''Asiyah''' ({{lang-ar|آسية}}), sometimes called '''Asiya bint Muzahim''', is revered by Muslims as one of the four best women of all time, the other three being [[Maryam, mother of Jesus|Mary]] (mother of [[Jesus]]), [[Khadija bint Khuwaylid|Khadija]] (wife of [[Muhammad]]) and [[Fatimah]] (daughter of Muhammad).<ref>Encyclopaedia of the Qur’an. Leidan: Brill, 2001. Print.</ref> She is described in the [[Quran]] as the wife of [[Pharaohs in the Bible#Pharaohs in the Book of Exodus|the Pharaoh]], who reigned during the time of [[Moses]] (''[[Moses in Islam|Musa]]''). She is believed to have secretly accepted [[monotheism]] after witnessing the miracle of Moses in her husband's court. The tradition holds that Asiya worshipped [[God in Islam|God]] in secret and prayed in disguise fearing her husband. She died while being tortured by her husband, who had discovered her monotheism and retaliated to her rebellion against his tyranny.<ref>Stowasser, B.F. (1994). Women in the qur’an, traditions, and interpretation. New York: Oxford University Press. 57</ref>
[[File:Asiya finds Moses.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Asiya (depicted with long black tresses) and her servants, having finished bathing, find baby Moses in the Nile.<ref>{{cite book|title=Infants, Parents and Wet Nurses: Medieval Islamic Views on Breastfeeding and Their Social Implications|author=Avner Gilʻadi|publisher=Brill Publishers|isbn=9789004112230|year=1999}}</ref> Their clothes hang in the trees while the river waves and crests are done in the Chinese style. Illustration from the Persian ''[[Jami' al-tawarikh]]'']]
==Early life== Muslims believe that Asiya came from a rich family and that she was a very beautiful and generous woman. Her [[marriage]] to the Pharaoh was arranged. Unlike her husband, she was humble and accepted the faith that [[Moses in Islam|Moses]] and [[Aaron]] were preaching. Although she had exceeding wealth, she was not arrogant like the Pharaoh. She realized that faith was far more important and was thus exalted by God amongst the women of her generation.
==Adoption of Moses== Asiya and her maids were at the neighbouring [[Nile river]] one day. To their amazement, they found a crate floating in the river. Asiya immediately ordered that the crate be brought out on shore. The maids thought there was a treasure in the crate, but instead found a baby boy, [[Moses in Islam|Moses]]. Asiya instantly felt motherly love towards him. She told the Pharaoh about the baby. The incident has been described in the [[Quran]].
{{quote|And Pharaoh's wife said: A refreshment of the eye to me and to thee – slay him not; maybe he will be useful to us, or we may take him for a son. And they perceived not. ||[[Quran]]: Sura [[Al-Qasas]], verse 9<ref>{{Cite quran|28|9|s=ns}}:(Here is) joy of the eye, for me and for thee: slay him not. It may be that he will be use to us, or we may adopt him as a son." And they perceived not (what they were doing)</ref>}}
Asiya then offered Moses's mother to live in their household as his [[wet nurse]] and paid her for her services, unaware of their relationship.<ref name="Brinner">{{cite book|title=The children of Israel|publisher=SUNY Press|year=1991|isbn=0-7914-0688-1|location=|author1=Ṭabarī|author2=Brinner, William M.}}<!--|accessdate=2009-09-06--></ref><ref name="Wheeler">{{cite book|title=Prophets in the Quran: an introduction to the Quran and Muslim exegesis|last=Wheeler|first=Brannon M.|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|year=2002|isbn=0-8264-4957-3|location=}}<!--|accessdate=2009-09-06--></ref>
==Death== When she witnessed the death of a believing woman under her husband's torture, she declared her faith before Pharaoh who tried to turn her away from the faith, but Asiya refused to reject the God and the teaching of Moses. On the Pharaoh's order, she was tortured to death.<ref>{{cite book|title=Windows on the house of Islam: Muslim sources on spirituality and religious life|last=Renard Although the Quran says that she prayed to God to save her from Pharaoh and some Muslim traditions even say that she was migrated when Moses was delivering the Israelites.|first=John|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|year=1998|isbn=0-520-21086-7|location=University of California Press}}<!--|accessdate=2011-01-25--></ref>
==Legacy== It is said that Asiya was a sincere believer and that she fully submitted herself to [[Allah]], despite being the wife of Pharaoh. According to Hadith, she will be among the first women to enter Paradise because she accepted Moses's monotheism over Pharaoh's beliefs. The [[Qur'an]] mentions Asiya as an example to all Muslims<ref name="Wheeler"/><ref name="Renard">{{cite book |last=Renard |first=John |title=Windows on the house of Islam: Muslim sources on spirituality and religious life |publisher=University of California Press |location= |year=1998 |isbn=0-520-21086-7}}<!--|accessdate=2009-09-06--></ref><ref name="Turfe">{{cite book|title=Patience in Islam: sabr|last=Turfe|first=Tallal Alie|publisher=TTQ, INC.|year=1996|isbn=1-879402-32-7|location=}}<!--|accessdate=2009-09-06--></ref>
{{Quote|And God sets forth, as an example to those who believe the wife of Pharaoh: Behold she said: 'O my Lord! Build for me, in nearness to Thee, a mansion in the Garden, and save me from Pharaoh and his doings, and save me from those that do wrong' ||Qur'an, chapter 66 ([[At-Tahrim]]), verse 11<ref>{{Cite quran|66|11|s=ns}}: "And God sets forth, as an example to those who believe the wife of Pharaoh: Behold she said: 'O my Lord! Build for me, in nearness to Thee, a mansion in the Garden, and save me from Pharaoh and his doings, and save me from those that do wrong':"</ref>}}
[[Abu Musa Ashaari]] narrated that once the [[Islamic prophet]], [[Muhammad]] stated, {{quote|Many men reached perfection but none among the women reached perfection except [[Mary in Islam|Mary]], the daughter of [[Joachim#In Islam|Imran]]; and Asiya, Pharaoh's wife. ||[[Sahih Al-Bukhari]] Hadith 7.329<ref name="[[Sahih Al-Bukhari]]">Muhmmad al-Bukhari. Sahih Al-Bukhari Translated into English Prose by Muhammad Muhsin Khan. Hadith 7.329</ref>}}
