{{redirect-multi|2|Holger Danske|Ogier}}

[[File:Holger danske.jpg|thumb|[[Hans Peder Pedersen-Dan]]'s statue of Holger Danske in the [[casemate]]s at [[Kronborg]] castle, Denmark]]

'''Ogier the Dane''' ({{lang-fr|{{noitalics|'''Ogier le Danois''', '''Ogier de Danemarche'''}}}}; {{lang-da|{{noitalics|'''Holger Danske'''}}}}) is a [[legend]]ary knight of [[Charlemagne]] who appears in many [[Old French]] ''[[chanson de geste|chansons de geste]]''. In particular, he features as the protagonist in ''La chevalerie Ogier'' (ca. 1220), which belongs to the ''Geste de [[Doon de Mayence]]'' ("cycle of the rebellious vassals").<ref name=keller-medieval-france-ency /> The first part of this epic, the ''enfance''[''s''] (childhood exploits) of Ogier, is marked by his duel against a [[Saracen]] from whom he obtains the sword Corte, followed by victory over another Saracen opponent from whom he wins the horse Broiefort. In subsequent parts, Ogier turns into a rebel with cause, seeking refuge with the King of [[Lombardy]] and warring with Charlemagne for many years, until he is eventually reconciled when a dire need for him emerges after another Saracen incursion.

His character is a composite based on a historical Autcharius Francus who was aligned with king [[Desiderius]] of Lombardy against Charlemagne. The legend of a certain Othgerius buried in [[Meaux]] is also incorporated into the ''Chevalerie''. In Scandinavia he was first known as '''Oddgeir danski''' in the [[Old Norse]] prose translation ''[[Karlamagnús saga]]'', but later became more widely known as Holger Danske and was given the pedigree of being Olaf son of King [[Gøtrik]], in a Danish translation published in the 16th century. Holger Danske became a Danish folklore hero, with a [[sleeping hero]] motif attached to him.

== Historical references ==
The Ogier character is generally believed to be based on Autcharius Francus (or Otkerus),{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|"Autcharius" is the spelling as occurs in the ''Vita Hadriani'' (biography of [[Pope Adrian I]] in the ''[[Liber Pontificalis]]'', "Otkerus" in a work by a monk of St. Gall (fl. 885).{{sfnp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}<ref name="Wilson p. 330">{{harvp|Dunlop|Wilson|1906}}, Wilson's note 1 (p. 330)</ref>}} a [[Franks|Frankish]] knight who had served [[Carloman I|Carloman]] and escorted his widow and young children to [[Desiderius]], King of [[Lombardy]], but eventually surrendered to [[Charlemagne]].{{sfnp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|Knud Togeby objected to identifying with Autcharius, and proposed Audacar who led Charlemagne's troops in Bavaria.{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=19}}{{sfnp|Emden|1988|p=125}}}} The Ogier character could also have been partly constructed from the historical [[Adalgis]]<!--Adelgis--> (or Algisus), son of Desiderius, who played a similar role.{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|The exploits of "Algisus" is given full account in the ''[[Chronicon novaliciense]]''.<ref name=ludlow-novalesa />}}{{sfnp|Voretzsch|1931|p=208}}<ref name="ludlow-novalesa">{{harvp|Ludlow|1865}}, pp. 274ff, note.</ref> The ''[[chanson de geste]]'' does parallel this, and Ogier does seek refuge with the [[Lombardy|Lombardian]] king Didier or Désier (as Desiderius is styled in French).{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|pp=265–273}}

An unrelated Othgerius (Otgerius), a benefactor buried at the Abbey of [[Saint Faro]] in [[Meaux]] in France,{{Efn|Bédier's characterization was that this Othgerius had no distinction besides having donated some parcels of land to the abbey and being buried there ({{harvp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}).}} became connected with Ogier by a work called ''Conversio Othgeri militis'' (ca. 1070–1080) written by the monks there.{{sfnp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}<ref name=shepard /> This tradition is reflected in the ''chanson'' of Ogier, which states that the hero was buried at Meaux.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|p=301}}

There is no Ogier of consequence in Danish history; at least, no Ogier as such appears in [[Saxo Grammaticus]]'s ''[[Gesta Danorum]]''.<ref name="nordisk">{{citation|title=Holger Danske |work=[[Nordisk familjebok]] |year=1909 |url=http://runeberg.org/nfbk/0516.html}} {{sv icon}}</ref> However, the Danish work ''Holger Danskes Krønike'' (1534) made Ogier into the son of [[Gudfred|King Gøtrek]] of Denmark{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|"Gøtrek" is the spelling in {{harvp|Hanssen|1842}} edition of the text. But there are various spellings: "Godfred",<ref name="nordisk" /> etc.}}<ref name=jensen>{{citation|last=Jensen |first=Janus Møller |title=Denmark and the Crusades, 1400–1650 |publisher=BRILL |year= 2007 |url=http://runeberg.org/nfbk/0516.html |isbn=9789047419846}}</ref><ref name="nordisk" /> (namely Olaf son of Gøtrek,<ref>{{harvp|Hanssen|1842|p=4}}: "Saa lod han ham christne og kaldte ham Oluf; men jeg vil kalde ham Olger (Then he was Baptized and christened Oluf, but I shall call him Ogier)".</ref> mentioned by Saxo). "Olgerus, dux Daniæ" ("Olger, War-Leader of the Danes") had rebuilt the St. Martin's monastery pillaged by the [[Saxons]] in 778, according to the chronicle of this monastery at [[Cologne]] (ca. 1050). However, this is not a contemporary record and may just be poetic fiction.<ref name="Wilson p. 330"/><ref name="nordisk" />

== Sword Cortain ==
Ogier the Dane had a sword named Cortain (also spelled Courtain, Cortana, Curtana, etc.) This name is the [[accusative case]] declension of Old French ''corte'', meaning "short".{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=17}}

The tradition that Ogier had a short sword is quite old. There is an entry for "Oggero ''spata curta''" ("Ogier of the short sword") in the {{illm|Nota Emilianense{{!}}''Nota Emilianense''|es|Nota Emilianense}} (ca. 1065–1075),<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Sholod |first=Barton |title=Charlemagne in Spain: The Cultural Legacy of Roncesvalles |publisher=Librairie Droz |year=1966|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RF5RMtPJBiMC&pg=PA189 |page=189}}</ref> and this is taken as a nickname derived from his sword-name Cortain.{{sfnp|Togeby|1966|p=112}} The sword name does not appear in the oldest extant copy of ''La chanson de Roland'' (Oxford manuscript), only in versions postdating the ''Nota''.<ref>{{harvp|Togeby|1966|p=112}} and {{harvp|Togeby|1969|p=17}}</ref> According to the first part (''enfances'') of ''Chevalerie Ogier'', the sword, which once belonged to Brumadant the Savage, was remade more than twenty times; finally it was tested on a block of marble and broke about a palm's length. It was reforged and named Corte or Cortain, meaning "short".{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|p=256}} This became the weapon of a [[chivalry|chivalric]]-minded [[Saracen]] named Karaheut,{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|name="karaheut"|"Karaheut" in {{harvp|Ludlow|1865}} and {{harvp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}; The ''courtois'' "Karaheu" in {{harvp|Togeby|1969|p=51}}. Langlois, ''{{url|https://books.google.com/books?id=IuIWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA132| Table&nbsp;des&nbsp;noms}}'', p. 132, lists "Caraheu, Craheut, Karaheu, Karaheut, Karaheult, Kareeu". "Karahues" and "Karahuel" are also used.}} who gives it to Ogier so he can fight Brunamont in single combat.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|p=260}}<ref name="vandijk-dict-mediev-heroes" />  The sword has appeared in chansons de geste somewhat predating ''Chevalerie Ogier'', or composed around the same time as it, such as ''[[Aspremont (chanson de geste)|Aspremont]]'' (before 1190) and ''[[Renaut de Montauban]]'' (c. 1200).{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=52}}

The ''[[Prose Tristan]]'' (1230–1235, expanded in 1240<ref name=curtis-dates />) states that Ogier inherited the sword of the Arthurian knight [[Tristan]], shortening it and thus naming it ''Cortaine''.{{Efn|This passage is not included in {{harvp|Curtis|1994}}'s English translation.<!--or her edition up to volume 3 [?]-->}}<ref name="loeseth">{{citation|last=Löseth |first=Eilert |title=Analyse critique du Roman de Tristan en prose française |place=Paris |publisher=Bouillon |year=1890 |page=302 |url=https://archive.org/stream/analysecritiqued00lsuoft#page/302/mode/2up/}} {{fr icon}}</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Loomis |first=Roger Sherman |title=Tristram and the House of Anjou |journal=The Modern Language Review |volume=17 |number=1 |year=1922 |page=29 <!--24–30--> |url=https://archive.org/stream/modernlanguager05assogoog#page/n40/mode/2up}}</ref> The English monarchy also laid claim to owning "Tristram's sword",{{Efn|King Johan received "duos enses scilicet ensem Tristrami.. (two swords, namely Tristram's sword.. )", [[Patent Rolls]] for 1207.}} and this according to [[Roger Sherman Loomis]] was the "Curtana" ("short") used in the [[coronation of the British monarch]].{{Efn|Loomis also argues that Curtana's origins as Tristram's sword was known to the author of this passage in Prose Tristan, but the tradition was forgotten in England.}}

== French sources ==
Ogier the Dane's first appearance (spelled ''Oger'') in any work is in ''[[Chanson de Roland]]'' (c. 1060),{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=17}} where he is not named as one of the douzepers (twelve peers or [[paladin]]s) of Charlemagne, although he is usually one of the twelve peers in other works.<ref>{{citation|last=Cresswell |first=Julia |title=Charlemagne and the Paladins |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |year=2014 |pages=20–21 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=147280418X&pg=PA20}}</ref> In the poeticized [[Battle of Ronceveaux Pass|Battle of Ronceveaux]], Ogier is assigned to be the vanguard and commands the Bavarian Army in the battle against [[Baligant]] in the later half.<ref name=baker /><ref name=vandijk-dict-mediev-heroes /> He plays only a minor part in this poem, and it is unclear what becomes of him, but the ''[[Pseudo-Turpin]]'' knows of a tradition that Ogier was killed at [[Roncevaux]].{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=28}}

A full career of Ogier from youth to death is treated in ''La Chevalerie Ogier de Danemarche'', a 13th-century assonanced poem of approximately 13,000 lines{{Efn|More than 13,000 in the Barrois edition, less in Eusebi's edition.}} attributed to Raimbert de Paris. It relates Ogier's early years, his rebellion against Charles and eventual reconciliation.<ref name=keller-medieval-france-ency/> This is now considered a retelling.{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|[[Joseph Bédier|Bédier]] called it a "''remaniement'' (reworking)",{{sfnp|Bédier|1908|loc='''2''', pp. 184–185}} but this term is also used by Keller to refer to the Alexandrine version.}} Ogier in a lost original "''Chevalerie Ogier'' primitive"{{Efn|Bédier's term}} is thought to have fought alongside the Lombards because Charlemagne attacked at the Pope's bidding, as historically happened in the [[Siege of Pavia (773–74)]],{{sfnp|Bédier|1908|loc='''2''', pp. 184–185}} that is, there was no fighting with the Saracens as a prelude to this.

The legend that Ogier fought valiantly with some Saracens in his youth is the chief material of the first branch (about 3,000 lines{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|3102 lines in Barrois's edition.{{sfnp|Barrois|1842|loc='''I''', p. lxxv}}{{sfnp|Henry (ed.)|Adenet|1956|p=21}}}}) of Raimbert's ''Chevalerie Ogier''.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|pp=249–261}} This is also recounted in ''Enfances Ogier'' (c. 1270), a rhymed poem of 9,229 lines by [[Adenet le Roi]]. The story of Ogier's youth develops with close similarity in these two works starting at the beginning, but they diverge at a certain point when Raimbert's version begins to be more economical with the details.{{sfnp|Henry (ed.)|Adenet|1956|pp=21, 24–25}}

Ogier in versions of the [[Renaissance]] travels to the [[Avalon]] ruled by [[King Arthur]] and eventually becomes [[Morgan le Fay]]'s paramour. This is how the story culminates in ''Roman d'Ogier'', a reworking in [[Alexandrines]] written in the 14th century, as well as its prose redaction retitled ''Ogier le Danois'' (''Ogyer le Danois'') printed in a number of editions from the late 15th century onwards.<ref name=taylor/>{{Efn|The Alexandrines version may contain some vestiges of the lost 12th century ''Chevalerie Ogier''.<ref name=keller-medieval-france-ency/><!--This speculation may be more important from the pov of establishing the "original romance", but in general, Ogier's connection with Morgan or Avalon has drawn more attention.-->}}

There are also several texts that might be classed as "histories" which refer to Ogier. Girart d'Amiens' ''Charlemagne'' contains a variant of Ogier's ''enfances''.<ref>{{harvp|Granzow (ed.)|Girart d'Amiens|1908}}, ''Charlemagne''</ref>{{sfnp|Baker|2002|p=64}} [[Jean d'Outremeuse]]'s ''Ly Myreur des Histors'' writes of Ogier's combat with the ''capalus'' ([[Cath Palug|chapalu]]). [[Philippe Mouskes]]'s 13th-century ''Chronique rimée'' writes on Ogier's death.{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=112}}

==''Chevalerie Ogier''==
Ogier is the main character in the poem ''La Chevalerie Ogier de Danemarche'' (written ca. 1200–1215). Here he is the son of Geoffroy de Danemarche given as a hostage to Charlemagne. Ogier's son is slain by [[Charlot]], son of Charlemagne. Ogier attacks Charlot and demands his life in revenge,<!--Charlot is not killed here--> resulting in his banishment. Ogier wars with Charlemagne for seven years and survives prison for another seven years. They eventually make peace and Ogier goes to fight at Charlemagne's side against the Saracens, in which battle he slays the [[giant (mythology)|giant]] Brehus. The work consists of twelve parts (or "branches") of varying lengths.{{Efn|Barrois edited the text divided into theses branches, and made the determinations on where the divisions by the dropped capital letters in one of the manuscripts (ms. B). ({{harvp|Togeby|1969|p=46}}).}}{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=46}}

Ogier, a condemned hostage, is initially an unarmed spectator when Charles fights Saracens in Italy at the Pope's request. But when the French suffer a setback, Ogier joins the fight, seizing a flag and arms from a fleeing [[standard-bearer]], and is knighted by the king in gratitude.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|pp=249–252}} Next, Ogier accepts the challenge of single combat from the Saracen Karaheut,{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|name="karaheut"}} but enemies interrupt and abduct Ogier. Karaheut protests for Ogier's release, to no avail, and loses his engagement to the admiral's daughter.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|pp=252–259}} She now wishes to marry the newcomer on the battlefield, Brunamont of Maiolgre (Majorca), but her wish will only be granted if a champion fights against Brunamont, and she names Ogier. Ogier, armed with Karaheut's sword Cortain, vanquishes Brunamont and wins the horse Broiefort.{{sfnp|Ludlow|1865|pp=259–261}}{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=52}}

== ''Roman d'Ogier'' ==
The 14th-century ''Roman d'Ogier'' is a ''{{linktext|refacimento}}'' in Alexandrines{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|"''{{linktext|refacimento}}''" was the term employed by Pio Rajna<ref>{{citation|last=Rajna |first=Pio |title=Uggeri il Danese nella letteratura romanzesca degi Italiani |journal=Romania |volume=2 |year=1873 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4INAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA156 |page=156, note 1}} {{fr icon}}</ref> as well as by Paton. But this means "reworking", and the term has been indiscriminately applied to other works, not necessarily the Alexandrine version.}}{{sfnp|Paton|1903|p=74}} of 29,000 verses.<ref name="reiss&reiss&taylor"/><!--Fact-checked against Paton saying 18,000 verses more than Raimbert-->{{Efn|For a list of excerpts and summary, see {{harvp|Paton|1903|p=75}} notes 2 and 7.}} In this version, Ogier is fated to be taken away by Morgan le Fay to [[Avalon]] and become her paramour. This fate is set in motion while Ogier is still a newborn in his crib. Six [[wikt:fée|fée]]s visit the baby, each with a gift, and Morgan's gift is longevity and life living with her. Ogier has an enhanced career, even becoming King of England,{{Efn|He does rescue and marry the daughter of the king of England in the older version.}} and when he reaches the age of 100, he is shipwrecked by Morgan so he can be conveyed to Avalon. He returns after two hundred years to save France, and is given a firebrand which must not be allowed to be burnt down for him to remain alive.{{Efn|Ward notes the firebrand is a motif seen in the legend of [[Meleager]].}} Ogier tries to forfeit his life after accomplishing his task but is save by Morgan.{{sfnp|Ward|1883|loc='''I''', pp. 607–609}}<ref>{{citation|last=Child|first=Francis James|title=37. Thomas Rymer|work=The English and Scottish Popular Ballads|volume=I <!--Part 2-->|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1884|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m9IVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA319|page=319}}</ref> It states the Ogier and Morgan have a son named Meurvin, who himself became the subject of a lengthy Renaissance era romance.{{sfnp|Paton|1903|p=77}}

== Legend at Meaux ==
{{multiple image
|header = Mausoleum of the Abbey of St. Faro, Meaux<br />{{nobold|{{small|View [[:File:ActSanctOrdSBen1677-p664b - cropped-to-statues.jpg|entire right half]] / [[:File:ActSanctOrdSBen1735-p624.png|view entire illustration]] (from 1735 edition).}}}}
|image1=ActSanctOrdSBen1677-p664b - cropped-to-statues.jpg
|caption1=Othgerius/Ogier is one of two reclining tomb effigies on the sarcophagus at center.
|alt1=Othgerius/Ogier is one of two reclining tomb effigies on the sarcophagus at center.
|width=300 |height=
|align=right
|footer=―''Acta Sanctorum Ordinis S. Benedicti'' (1677 edition).
}}

A legend of ''Conversio Othgeri militis'' was invented by the monks at the abbey of [[Saint Faro]] at [[Meaux]] around 1070–1080. It claimed Othgerius Francus ("Frankish") to be the most illustrious member of Charlemagne's court after the king himself,{{sfnp|Cerf|1910|p=2}} thus making him identifiable with Ogier the Dane.{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|Various references cite this document ("Conversion of Othger") as being one (purportedly) about Ogier.<ref name=keller-medieval-france-ency /> Cerf even refers to the document as ''Conversio Ogeri militis'' ("Conversion of Ogier").{{sfnp|Cerf|1910}}}} He was buried in the abbey in a mausoleum built for him. His remains were placed in a [[sarcophagus]] lidded with his recumbent [[tomb effigy]] lying next to that of Saint Benedictus, and the chamber was enshrined with erect statues of various figures from the [[Matter of France|Charlemagne Cycle]].{{sfnp|Voretzsch|1931|p=209}}<ref name=shepard /><ref name=vandijk-dict-mediev-heroes />

This document was first commented on by [[Jean Mabillon]] in his ''Acta Sanctorum Ordinis S. Benedicti'',{{sfnp|Cerf|1910|p=2}} printed editions of which include a detailed illustration of the mausoleum at St. Faro. The statues at the mausoleum even included [[Aude (character)|la belle Aude]], affianced to Roland,<ref name="shepard" /> with one of the inscriptions there (according to Mabillon) claiming that Aude was Ogier's sister.{{sfnp|Togeby|1969|p=145}}{{sfnp|d'Achery|Mabillon|1677|p=661n}}{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|{{harvp|Togeby|1966|p=113}} states it differently, that the inscriptions agree with the chanson ''Girart de Vienne'' where Aude is [[Oliver (paladin)|Oliver]]'s sister. But Mabillon can be quoted thus: "..{{linktext|forsan |ab}} Auda matre, Otgerii nostri {{linktext|sorore}}, Rotlando {{linktext|nupta}}".}}<!--{{efn|Also, a confused 16th century necrology of St. Faro mistook a certain Ogier of [[Charmentray]] who became a monk at the abbey to be Ogier the Dane who lived 300 years before.{{sfnp|Cerf|1910|p=9}}}}--> It underwent restoration in 1535 by the Italian Gabriele Simeoni.{{Efn|This is pointed out by {Philipp August Becker, state by Mabillon.}}<ref>{{citation|last=Becker|first=Philipp August |title=Ogier Von Dänemark |journal=Zeitschrift für französische Sprache und Literatur |volume=64 |number=1 |year=1942 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KbYMAAAAIAAJ |page=75, note 4<!--67–-88-->}} {{jstor|40615765}} {{de icon}}</ref>{{sfnp|d'Achery|Mabillon|1677|p=664}} That mausoleum is no longer  preserved, but an illustration of the interior was printed in editions of Mabillon's ''Acta Sanctorum Ordinis S. Benedicti''.<ref>{{citation|last1=d'Achery |first1=Lucas |last2=Mabillon |first2=Jean |title=Acta Sanctorum Ordinis S. Benedicti: Pars Prima |volume=IV |publisher=apud Ludovicum Billaine, in Palatio Regio |year=1677 |url=https://books.google.com/books/content?id=KBDsYnABUeIC&pg=PA664-IA2 |page=664}} {{la icon}}</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Mabillon |first=Jean |title=Acta Sanctorum Ordinis S. Benedicti: Pars Prima |volume=IV |publisher=Coletus & Bettinellus |year=1735  |url=https://books.google.com/books/content?id=rt1JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA624-IA2 |page=624}} {{la icon}}</ref> 

[[File:Bulletin arch du comite(1905)-Pl XI-tete-meaux.jpg|thumb|120px|Ogier head at Meaux|left]]

A stone head later found in Meaux was determined to be Ogier's head from comparisons with these incunabula etchings.<ref name="gassies">{{citation|last=Gassies |first=Georges |title=Note sur une tête de statue touvée à Meaux |journal=Bulletin archéologique du Comité des travaux historiques et scientifiques |year=1905 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YT4ZQOHmG_sC&pg=PA40 |pages=40–42}}</ref> This stone head can still be viewed today.

== Scandinavia ==
[[File:Holger Danske i Skævinge kirke.jpg|thumb|upright|Ogier the Dane (left) in a 16th-century church mural in [[Skævinge]], Denmark]]

The early form of the ''chanson de geste'' was translated in the 13th century into Old Norse as ''Oddgeirs þáttr danska'' ("Story of Oddgeir danski"), Branch III of the ''[[Karlamagnús saga]]''. An Old Danish version of it, ''Karl Magnus krønike'', was later created (some copies date to 1480).{{sfnp|Layher|2004|p=93}}

The 16th-century ''Olger Danskes krønike'' was a Danish translation of the French prose romance ''Ogier le Danois'' by [[Kristiern Pedersen]], started while in Paris in 1514–1515, probably completed during his second sojourn in 1527, and printed in 1534 in [[Malmö]].<ref name=jensen /><ref name="nordisk" /> Pedersen also fused the romance with Danish genealogy, thus making Ogier the son of Danish king Gøtrik ([[Godfred]]).{{sfnp|Hanssen|1842|p=1}}<ref name="nordisk" />

=== Balladry ===
"Holger Danske og Burmand" ([[Danmarks gamle Folkeviser|DgF]] 30, [[The Types of the Scandinavian Medieval Ballad|TSB]] E&nbsp;133) recounts the fight between the hero and Burmand, described as a giant (and not a Saracen).{{sfnp|Layher|2004|p=93}} The [[ballad]] also exists in Swedish ([[Sveriges Medeltida Ballader|SMB]] 216) and tells the story of how Holger Dansk is released from prison to fight against a [[troll]] by the name of Burman.{{sfnp|Layher|2004|p=98}}<ref>The Faraway North, Scandinavian Folk Ballads, I. Cumpstey, 2016 ({{ISBN|978-0-9576120-2-0}})</ref>

=== Kronborg legend ===
Similar to [[Frederick Barbarossa]], [[Saint Wenceslas]] and [[King Arthur]], Ogier in Danish legend becomes a [[king in the mountain]]; he is said to dwell in the castle of [[Kronborg]], his beard grown down to the floor. He will sleep there until some day when the country of Denmark is in peril, at which time he will rise up and save the nation. This is a common folklore motif, classed as Type 1960.2, "[[King in the mountain|The King Asleep in the Mountain]]".<ref>{{citation|last=Baughman |first=Ernest W. |title=Type and Motif-Index of the Folktales of England and North America |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |year=1966 |page=122 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uk-W8g_68b8C&pg=PA122}}</ref> According to the tour guides of Kronborg Castle, legend has it that Holger sat down in his present location after walking all the way from his complete battles in France.

The 1789 opera ''[[Holger Danske (opera)|Holger Danske]]'', composed by [[F.L.Æ. Kunzen]] with a [[libretto]] by [[Jens Baggesen]], had a considerable impact on Danish nationalism in the late 18th century. It spawned the literary "Holger feud", which revealed the increasing dissatisfaction among the native Danish population with the German influence on Danish society. The Danish intellectual [[Peter Andreas Heiberg]] joined the feud by writing a satirical version entitled ''Holger Tyske'' ("Holger the German") ridiculing Baggesen's lyrics. During the [[Denmark in World War II|German occupation of Denmark]], presentation of the same opera in Copenhagen became a manifestation of Danish national feeling and opposition to the occupation.

== In art ==
The hero's popularity led to him being depicted on 15th- and 16th-century paintings in two churches in Denmark and Sweden.<ref name="nordisk" />  The Holger Danske and Burman painted on the ceiling of [[Flodafors|Floda Church]] in Sweden are attributed to [[Albertus Pictor]] around 1480. It also includes the text ''Holger Dane won victory over Burman''; this is the [[Refrain|burden]] of the Danish and Swedish ballad, but the painting predates other written texts for this ballad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christermalmberg.se/pictor/kyrkor/floda.php|title=Albertus Pictor - Floda kyrka|first=Christer|last=Malmberg|website=christermalmberg.se}}</ref>{{sfnp|Layher|2004|pp=90–92}}

The [[Hotel Marienlyst]] in [[Helsingør]] commissioned a statue of Holger Danske in 1907 from the sculptor [[Hans Peder Pedersen-Dan]]. The bronze statue was outside the hotel until 2013, when it was sold and moved to [[Skjern, Denmark|Skjern]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/magasinet/feature/art5514650/Nu-sover-Holger-Danske-i-Skjern|title=Nu sover Holger Danske i Skjern|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://nyheder.tv2.dk/article.php/id-67626386%3Aholger-danske-ryger-til-skjern-solgt-for-rekordbel%C3%83%C2%83%C3%82%C2%83%C3%83%C2%82%C3%82%C2%B8b.html</ref> The bronze statue was based on an original in plaster. The plaster statue was placed in the vaults at [[Kronborg castle]], also in Helsingør, where it became a popular attraction in its own right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kongeligeslotte.dk/da/slotte-og-haver/kronborg-slot/udforsk-kronborg-slot/holger-danske.html|title=Holger Danske - Udforsk slottet - Kronborg Slot - Slotte og haver - Kongelige Slotte|website=kongeligeslotte.dk}}</ref> The plaster statue was replaced by a concrete copy in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitdenmark.com/denmark/holger-danske-ogier-dane-gdk784308|title=Holger Danske - Ogier the Dane|publisher=}}</ref>

== Eponyms ==
* The largest [[World War II]] [[Danish resistance movement|Danish resistance]] group, [[Holger Danske (resistance group)|Holger Danske]], was named after the legend.
* On the slopes of Rönneberga outside Landskrona in south Sweden (formerly a part of Denmark), there is a burial mound named Holger Danske mound.

== Popular culture ==
* In [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s poem "The Land" (1916), "Ogier the Dane" is the archetypal name used to signify Danish invaders who have overran [[Sussex]] over the years.
* In [[Poul Anderson]]'s fantasy novel ''[[Three Hearts and Three Lions]]'' (1961), Danish Resistance member Holger Carlsen time warps and learns that he is Ogier the Dane.
* In [[Per Petterson]]'s ''I Curse the River of Time'' (2001), there is a ferry named ''Holger Danske''.{{Efn|Translated into English by Charlotte Barslund from the Norwegian. The ferry sails between Norway and Denmark.}}

